1. Satya Yuga (The Golden Age)

Duration: 1,728,000 Human Years
Theme: Krita Yuga (The Age of Completion/Truth)
Dominant Quality: Sattva (Purity, Clarity)

In the Satya Yuga, the "Bull of Dharma" stands firmly on four legs. Humans live for 100,000 years, and the world is in direct communion with the divine.

The Chain of Creation: From Silence to the Storm

The cycle begins with Brahma vibrating the sacred sound Om, manifest as the four Vedas. However, a shadow falls immediately: the Vedas are stolen by the demons Madhu and Kaitabha. This theft triggers a chain of divine rescues where every solution reveals a deeper instability.

The Interlinked Avatars: One Rescue Leads to Another

The Flood and the Secret (Matsya): As Vishnu descends as Matsya the Fish to retrieve the Vedas, he warns King Satyavrata of a global Pralaya (flood). But even as he pulls the ark to safety, he reveals a terrifying truth: the Earth is sinking into the abyss, dragged down by the demon Hiranyaksha.

The Depths and the Boar (Varaha): Vishnu immediately becomes Varaha the Boar to hoist the Earth back to the surface. He slays Hiranyaksha, but this death creates a vacuum of vengeance. Hiranyaksha's brother, Hiranyakashipu, begins a penance so intense it threatens to melt the heavens.

The Churning of Chaos (Kurma): To combat the rising demonic tide, the Gods must churn the Ocean of Milk for the nectar of immortality. When the mountain they use as a rod begins to sink, Vishnu becomes Kurma the Tortoise to support it. The nectar is recovered, but it only fuels the rage of Hiranyakashipu, who has now used his boons to become seemingly unkillable.

The Climax: The Impossible Execution (Narasimha)

The Satya Yuga reaches its pitch with Narasimha. Hiranyakashipu cannot be killed by man or beast, inside or outside, day or night. The loop closes when Vishnu shatters a pillar to emerge as the Man-Lion, slaying the tyrant at twilight on a threshold. The world is saved, but the absolute purity of the age begins to crack.
